\
LOCKED FILTERS (TAGS)
\b0 \
It's important that users can create locked filters (tags with permissions). For instance, as owner of playpoi I may want to create "Playpoi affiliated teachers" which would display all teachers officially related to Playpoi. These tags could only be applied to individuals by myself or anybody I gave permission to. 
\f1 \
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\cf0 \
Thus I can create the "friends of playpoi" tag and give permission to my friends to tag events as such. I trust Jon to make good choices. I can set whether others can in turn pass permission onwards. \
\
With this approach, the vitality of the flow-map will be based on a growing and dynamic series of relationships and goodwill between artist communities and website owners. The global views will always allow users to find all poi teachers, all events, etc. But of course this won't guarantee quality. Thus networks of quality assurance will arise naturally. Want your event to be Playpoi-Approved? Great! Fly one of us over to the first event and if it's awesome we'll approve it from then on! \
\
\
\

\b AVOIDING ABUSE
\b0 \
Generally, our method to avoid clutter and abuse is to develop a very good system of taxonomy and tools for site owners. This will include an either/or system for designating the event. If an event can only be regional OR international, that would force users to make the appropriate choice. If I am teaching local poi lessons in Toronto, I want it to appear when people zoom in to Toronto. If I were to falsely tag my lessons as international, they would only appear in the international-events layer, and thus people looking for local poi resources would not find me. \
\
Note that non-international events, such as public spin-jams, are unlikely to be abused anyway, and will only appear when the viewer zooms into a specified location. \
\
The mostly likely way people will try to abuse the map is to tag their events as international when they are not, in the hopes of getting more attention for the event. \

\f0 \

